 Romania, Feb 5 (bdnews24.com/Reuters)-- In an unexpected move, Romania accepts Washington's offer to host part of a missile shield to protect Europe. Deborah Lutterbeck reports. Romania says yes to a US missile shield. Romania's top defense body accepted Washington's offer to deploy interceptor missiles as part of a missile shield to protect Europe President Traian Basescu. SOUNDBITE: President Traian Basescu, saying (Romanian): "Terrestrial interceptors will be located inside the national territory. According to the timetable agreed with the US, the anti-missile system will be operational in Romania starting 2015. The new system is not against Russia. I want to categorically stress this, Romania does not host a system against Russia, but against other threats." (CAMERAMEN) "The CSAT decision respects the country's constitution and laws and any public debates around the anti-missiles shield should take it into account." Basescu gave few details on the project, but it appeared to be part of the revamped approach taken by Obama White House, which scrapped a Bush-era plan for a radar site and interceptor rockets in the Czech Republic and Poland. The missile shield had angered Russian leaders who saw it as a threat to its own nuclear arsenal and bristled at what they saw as meddling by Washington in its sphere of influe
